SATIRE VIII.

Trm vice of aristocratic pretension is here represented with mode- ration and good sense. There is no idle declamation against heredi· tary honors3 but the blindness of men belonging to an exclusive class, whose claims to distinction were founded upon the merits of the great and good of former generations and unsupported by any personal merits of their own, is shown in language to which no one can object and reasoning which admits of no answer. The Satire is in the form of a letter addressed to one Pontius. He is one of the class against whose degenerate members the Satire is directed ; and we may sup-

ose he was a young man with what we should call good prospects. g'he ride of birth and the degeneracy of inheritcd nobility were not new eatures of society in Juvenal’s time, and they have not grown so old in ours but that generations to come will complain as he did, and pour contempt, as he did not, on the inheritance of noble names, however virtuous their possessors may be.
